<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Minister Leaves for Russia Via Tokyo </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Minister Leaves for Russia Via Tokyo </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1204061094 Tokyo KYODO in English 0602 GMT 12 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1204061094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, April 12 KYODO -- South Korean Foreign 
Minister Han Sung-chu flew to Tokyo on Tuesday [12 April] on his 
way for a weeklong visit to Russia, Britain and Belgium, 
government officials said. 
  During a stopover in Tokyo, Han will meet Hans Blix, 
director 
general of the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA), to 
discuss North Korea's refusal to grant inspectors unhampered 
access to its nuclear facilities. 
  The IAEA has said two weeks of inspections in March were 
insufficient to decide whether Pyongyang has diverted nuclear 
materials for weapons purposes as alleged by the United States 
and other Western nations. 
  North Korea says it has fully complied with inspection 
criteria previously agreed upon and maintains its nuclear 
program serves strictly civilian purposes. 
  The nuclear row will top Han's agenda in Moscow, where he 
will meet Russian Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev and other 
government leaders from Wednesday through Friday. 
  "I expect Moscow to bring up its earlier proposal for an 
eight- way conference on the North Korean nuclear issue and I 
will explain Seoul's position," YONHAP News Agency quoted Han as 
saying before departure. 
  Moscow has suggested that both Koreas, China, the U.S., 
Russia, Japan, the United Nations and the IAEA try to resolve 
the nuclear controversy through a special conference. 
  According to YONHAP, Han said Seoul welcomes the Russian 
proposal but prefers that the UN handles the North Korean issue 
for the time being. 
  Han is scheduled to meet British Foreign Secretary Douglas 
Hurd in London on Saturday and will return to Seoul next Monday 
after attending a two-day conference of South Korean mission 
chiefs in Brussels. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

