<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-070 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  8 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Former Opposition Leader Favors DPRK Dialogue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Former Opposition Leader Favors DPRK Dialogue </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK0804024594 Seoul YONHAP in English 0204 GMT 8 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0804024594 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, April 8 (YONHAP) -- Kim Tae-chung, chairman 
of the Asia-Pacific Peace Foundation, declaring that North 
Korea's nuclear program must be stopped at any cost, said Friday 
that a "package solution" and use of "the China card" are the 
only way. 
  "A military confrontation against reckless provocation by 
the 
North Korean hard-liners has to be avoided," Kim said in a 
prepared text for his lecture at Pusan University. 
  The package solution Kim was referring to has also been 
proposed by North Korea. It aims at resolving the nuclear 
dispute through an overall package deal with the United States 
calling for, among other things, normalization of relations 
between Washington and Pyongyang. 
  South Korea and the United States should not resume their 
joint military exercise "Team Spirit" as it would impede 
dialogue, Kim said. 
  Seoul will have to reconsider deploying Patriot missiles or 
purchasing other new military weapons, said the former leader of 
the opposition Democratic Party. 
  "Nuclear proliferation has to be stopped not only in North 
Korea but also in other countries," Kim said, adding that the 
United States, Russia, France, Britain and China must show their 
commitment to making the world free of nuclear weapons. 
  It isn't very persuasive for these big powers to oppose the 
possession of relatively cheap but hugely destructive nuclear 
bombs by smaller countries while they have their own nuclear 
weapons, Kim argued. 
  South and North Korea, the United States, Russia, Japan and 
China must undertake a serious study of security in Northeast 
Asia, including the matter of keeping the region nuclear free, 
Kim said. 
  Such a study would provide a means to resolve the North 
Korean nuclear issue as well as help maintain peace and 
stability in Northeast Asia, he added. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-5574 </DOCNO>
