<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Urged To Review Nuclear Policy </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government Urged To Review Nuclear Policy </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1204061394 Seoul CHUNGANG ILBO in Korean 12 Apr 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> SK1204061394 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul CHUNGANG ILBO </F>
<F P=105>  Korean </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Members of the Advisory Committee of the ROK Foreign 
Ministry have urged the government to fully review its nuclear 
policy indicating that the third round of U.S.-North Korean 
high-level talks can be held only if the exchange of special 
envoys between the North and South is held. The government has 
so far made efforts to resolve the North Korean nuclear issue. 
  Members of the "Unification Subcommittee" under the Foreign 
Ministry Policy Advisory Committee -- which includes scholars, 
journalists, and former Foreign Ministry authorities -- held a 
behind-closed-doors meeting at the Foreign Ministry on 11 April 
with the presence of high-level Foreign Ministry officials, 
including Pak Su-kil, chairman of the Institute of Foreign 
Affairs and National Security. They agreed that it is desirable 
not to link the exchange of special envoys with the third round 
of U.S.-North Korean high-level talks. 
  Participants in that meeting said: "The UN Security Council 
president's statement has called upon North Korea to accept 
additional nuclear inspections by early May, at the latest. 
Therefore, the government should not link the exchange of 
special envoys with the nuclear inspections in order to make 
North Korea accept the additional nuclear inspections by then. 
  Such recommendation by the Advisory Committee members has 
been made at a time when the ROK, the United States, and the 
International Atomic Energy Agency have made efforts to seek the 
multilateral plans to resolve the North Korean nuclear issues. 
Thus, it attracts the people's attention. 
  They said that "either U.S. Secretary of Defense William 
Perry or U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher had stated 
that diplomatic efforts to get North Korea to allow 
international inspections of its nuclear facilities will last 
another six months," and that "there are some signs of change in 
the U.S. position toward North Korea." 
  They have pointed out that there are differences in opinions 
between the ROK and U.S. Governments regarding the North Korean 
nuclear issue. They also stressed that the government should 
comprehensively review its nuclear policy toward North Korea and 
formulate concrete plans to resolve the North Korean nuclear 
issue. 
  Furthermore, some participants said that the government 
should not be restricted by time during nuclear negotiations 
with North Korea, and that it should be patient in resolving the 
North Korean nuclear issue, while properly using both a hardline 
and moderate policy. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

