<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kim Tae-chung Urges `Soft Policy' on DPRK </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kim Tae-chung Urges `Soft Policy' on DPRK </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK0904032694 Seoul YONHAP in English 0254 GMT 9 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0904032694 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Taegu, April 9 (YONHAP) -- Former opposition leader 
Kim Tae-chung said Saturday that hard-liners in Seoul, Pyongyang 
and Washington are hampering solution of the North Korean 
nuclear dispute. 
  Kim, chairman of the Kim Tae-chung Peace Foundation for the 
Asia- Pacific Region, told nearly 150 supporters here that the 
government should adopt a soft policy toward North Korea in 
order to bring about change. 
  "The Cold War age is over and the conditions causing 
division 
of the Korean peninsula have disappeared. So if South and North 
Korea continue their exhausting competition, both will turn into 
third- rate countries," he warned. 
  Kim called on the government to solve the nuclear problem 
through a "package deal," under which Western countries would 
recognize the Pyongyang Government while North Korea gave up 
nuclear weapons. In doing so, the government should secure the 
cooperation of China, he said. 
  "North Korea will eventually abandon nuclear weapons and the 
United States will establish an embassy in Pyongyang," he 
predicted. 
  This was Kim's first visit to Taegu since he was defeated in 
the presidential election in December 1992. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

