<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Seoul Rejects DPRK's Liaison Contact Proposal </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Seoul Rejects DPRK's Liaison Contact Proposal </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1204090194 Seoul YONHAP in English 0854 GMT 12 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1204090194 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, April 12 (YONHAP) -- South Korea turned down 
Tuesday a North Korean proposal to take delivery of a letter, 
rebuffing the suggestion as "turning the other way from the 
normal inter-Korean dialogue channel" and "of no help to 
improving relations." 
  Yi Chun-ku, Seoul's liaison officer, phoned his Pyongyang 
counterpart Yi Song-tok to say that South Korea will not accept 
the letter. 
  Pyongyang had notified Seoul Monday that it wanted to 
deliver 
a letter Wednesday addressed to the South Korean Government, 
political parties, social organizations and individuals. 
  Officials here said the letter is believed to ask Southern 
figures to participate in a conference on Aug. 15, the 49th 
anniversary of Korean liberation from Japanese colonial rule, of 
party and social leaders on ending national division. 
  Unification Board Spokesman Kim Hyong-ki issued a statement 
accusing North Korea of attempting yet "another tactic on the 
unification front." 
  "Stop political propaganda which only stirs up distrust and 
confrontation among the people," the statement said. 
  Kim urged North Korea to realize the mood of the 
international community and accept nuclear inspections and 
resumption of inter- Korean dialogue. 

</TEXT>

