<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Assembly Committee Cancels Loggers Survey Team </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Assembly Committee Cancels Loggers Survey Team </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1204120994 Seoul YONHAP in English 1150 GMT 12 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1204120994 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, April 12 (YONHAP) -- The National Assembly 
Foreign Affairs and Unification Committee has in effect 
cancelled a plan to send a fact-finding team to Russia to look 
into the human rights conditions of North Korean loggers in 
Siberia. 
  The committee initially planned to send four of its 
legislators to Moscow and Khabarovsk to observe loggers' 
conditions before a special assembly sitting opens in May. 
  "The dispatch of a fact-finding team is not always needed in 
determining the conditions of North Korean loggers there," Kang 
Sin- che, chairman of the committee's ad hoc committee on North 
Korean loggers, said on Tuesday. 
  He said Foreign Minister Han Sung-chu visits Moscow in the 
immediate future and there have been other frequent contacts 
between the two countries over the diplomatic channel. 
  Kang said he was withholding the dispatch. But, the plan 
seems to have been scrapped altogether. 
  "At the moment, we have no plan to send a survey team to 
Russia," an official of the Foreign Affairs and Unification 
Committee said. 

</TEXT>

