Daily Report 
<DATE1>  11 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ambassador Assures Washington Reform To Continue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ambassador Assures Washington Reform To Continue </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1104234394 Tokyo KYODO in English 2325 GMT 11 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1104234394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Washington, April 11 KYODO -- Japan's Ambassador to 
the United States Takakazu Kuriyama assured Washington Monday 
that the new government in Tokyo will press on with political 
and economic reform initiated by outgoing Prime Minister 
Morihiro Hosokawa. Japanese diplomatic sources said Kuriyama 
gave his assurance in a meeting with U.S. Trade Representative 
Mickey Kantor. 
  Kuriyama originally asked for the meeting to set the 
groundwork for crucial trade talks that had been scheduled for 
Friday in Morocco between Kantor and Japanese Foreign Minister 
Tsutomu Hata. 
  The surprise announcement last Friday that Hosokawa was 
stepping down from office is likely to scuttle Hata's planned 
trip to Morocco, however, as well as prospects for a quick 
resumption of stalled trade talks between Tokyo and Washington. 
  Japanese diplomatic sources said Kantor and Kuriyama agreed 
that the two countries should act prudently on the "framework" 
trade talks. "Both sides realized that the framework should not 
be allowed to fail once again," a Japanese source said. 
  Tokyo has urged Washington to resume the talks, which broke 
down at a summit meeting between President Bill Clinton and 
Hosokawa on Feb. 11. 
  The Clinton administration made it clear after Hosokawa's 
resignation announcement last Friday that Washington wants to 
settle trade disputes with Japan under the terms of the basic 
framework trade accord reached with Tokyo last summer. 

</TEXT>

