<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   PRC Urged To Persuade DPRK on Nuclear Issue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    PRC Urged To Persuade DPRK on Nuclear Issue </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1204062994 Seoul YONHAP in English 0601 GMT 12 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1204062994 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, April 12 (YONHAP) -- Ruling Democratic 
Liberal Party (DLP) chief policy-maker Yi Se-ki met Wu Xueqian, 
visiting vice chairman of the Chinese People's Political 
Consultative Conference, Tuesday to discuss the North Korean 
nuclear matter. 
  Rep. Yi expressed concern that if the problem is not 
resolved, there will be louder calls for the South to go nuclear 
as well, prompting Japan to do the same and leading to unbridled 
nuclear competition. 
  "This is what both Korea and China do not want," he said, 
tactfully urging Beijing to be more aggressive in persuading 
Pyongyang to halt its suspected nuclear arms program. 
  Wu, former deputy premier and foreign minister, explained 
that China wishes to see peace and security maintained on the 
Korean peninsula. "Although China's role is limited, we will 
continue our efforts to persuade North Korea," he said. 

</TEXT>

