<H3> <TI>   Hata Stresses Importance of Deregulation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Hata Stresses Importance of Deregulation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1104133894 Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database in Japanese 11 
Apr 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1104133894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN 11 April Evening Edition] </F>
  [Text] The government convened the second meeting of the 
Administrative Reform Headquarters' (headed by Prime Minister 
Morihiro Hosokawa) "Working Panel on Import Promotion, 
Improvement of Market Access, and Distribution" at the Prime 
Minister's Official Residence on the morning of 11 April. At 
the meeting, Tsutomu Hata, deputy prime minister and 
concurrently foreign minister, said: "Deregulation is a very 
important issue, since its implementation is beneficial from the 
standpoint of people's livelihood. For example, it will help 
reduce the gap of commodity prices at home and abroad. Despite 
the current political situation, it is desired that further 
efforts will be made toward this end." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-5622 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas071__a94015" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-071-A </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  13 April 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hosokawa Criticizes Meeting of Party Leaders </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Hosokawa Criticizes Meeting of Party Leaders </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1104133294 Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database in Japanese 11 
Apr 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1104133294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From ASAHI SHIMBUN 11 April Evening Edition] </F>
  [Text] On the afternoon of 11 April, Prime Minister 
Morihiro Hosokawa severely criticized a meeting of top leaders 
of three parties -- the Social Democratic Party of Japan [SDPJ], 
the Democratic Socialist Party [DSP], and Sakigake [Harbinger] 
-- and a floor group held earlier in the day. 
  At the Prime Minister's Office, Hosokawa told reporters: "I 
think the meeting is wrong. Since coalition parties have agreed 
to pick (the next prime minister) at the party representatives 
meeting [attended by party secretaries general], the meeting of 
party heads should be held after that. The coalition will not 
be able to reach an accord if the top-level meeting comes first." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

