Daily Report 
<DATE1>  12 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Parties Maneuver Toward New Alliances </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Parties Maneuver Toward New Alliances </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1204201094 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 12 Apr 
94 Morning Edition p 3--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1204201094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Shinseito [Japan Renewal Party] and Komeito, which 
have been considering plans for a recombination of parties in 
the coalition alliance on the condition of fielding the Liberal 
Democratic Party's [LDP] Michio Watanabe, former deputy prime 
minister and former foreign minister, for the prime 
ministership, are now being pressed to reconsider their 
strategies. Watanabe has shown a willingness to join hands with 
Shinseito and Komeito, but in such a case, the Social Democratic 
Party of Japan [SDPJ] and Sakigake [Harbinger] are certain to 
withdraw from the coalition alliance. Even if Watanabe were to 
bolt from the LDP, it would not be easy to fill the hole that 
would be left in the coalition alliance should the SDPJ and 
other groups leave the alliance. Shinseito and Komeito would 
then find themselves barred from carrying out their crucial task 
of forming a majority group. Apparently, the two parties have 
thus taken a "two-pronged approach": considering plans to 
maintain the framework of the current alliance with the SDPJ and 
other groups while flashing the "Watanabe negotiating card." 
  Initially, Shinseito planned to join "Reform" [Kaikaku], a 
new lower house parliamentary group formed by the Japan New 
Party [JNP] together with Komeito; the "Kaikaku-no-Kai" 
[parliamentary group formed by Takeo Nishioka and others who 
recently broke away from the LDP], and a group of lower house 
members from the Democratic Socialist Party of Japan [DSP] who 
are close to DSP Secretary General Takashi Yonezawa. Shinseito 
then planned to form a grand parliamentary alliance of 170-180 
members, making it the largest ruling coalition parliamentary 
bloc. It then planned to use this as a backdrop in a strategy 
to join hands with Watanabe and his supporters. 
  However, plans to form a majority group among the ruling 
coalition parties have not been proceeding as well as expected 
because, among other reasons, the formation of the "Kaikaku" has 
triggered a split in Hosokawa's own front yard, the JNP. On top 
of this, the assumption that "the SDPJ would never form an 
alliance with the LDP" (as stated by a senior Komeito official) 
turned out to be incorrect. With the emergence of a possible 
alliance between Sakigake, the SDPJ, and the LDP, from which 
Watanabe is expected to have defected, there has emerged the 
possibility that the Shinseito-led group may fall back into a 
minority. 
  On the afternoon of 10 April, rumors of an 
"LDP-SDPJ-Sakigake" alliance caused mixed reactions among 
Shinseito members. Some senior party officials suggested that 
the party place priority on maintaining the current coalition 
alliance and attend a party leadership meeting proposed by SDPJ 
Chairman Tomiichi Murayama in order to ease resistance against 
the so-called "Ichi-Ichi line" formed by Shinseito Secretary 
General Ichiro Ozawa and Komeito Secretary General Yuichi 
Ichikawa. Ozawa, however, rejected the leadership meeting, in 
insisting on launching a frontal assault. As for the meeting 
between Murayama and three other party leaders, Ozawa openly 
demonstrated his displeasure, saying: "Only half (of the ruling 
coalition party leaders) will be there. It will be nothing more 
than a private gathering." Another senior party official feels 
that should the "LDP-SDPJ-Sakigake" alliance plan proceed 
further, "there eventually will be a split in both the LDP and 
the SDPJ." A group of Shinseito members close to Ozawa has been 
contacting Watanabe behind the scenes, while a group of junior 
party members has been contacting the LDP's 
proelectoral-reformists who are close to former Prime Minister 
Toshiki Kaifu. 
  While such maneuverings are going on, Shinseito is also 
considering plans to maintain the framework of the current 
coalition alliance and to successfully field "Tsutomu Hata as 
the new prime minister." The party considers this as the "last 
point of compromise." In this case, however, it is certain that 
the SDPJ and other groups will demand that there be no more 
instances of "Ichi- Ichi line"-initiated steering of the 
government. A top DSP official has even insisted, "Ozawa and 
Ichikawa should be placed on their good behavior." In case 
agreement cannot be reached among the ruling coalition parties 
to choose Hata as Hosokawa's successor, there also remains the 
possibility that Murayama and Chief Cabinet Secretary Masayoshi 
Takemura may be fielded for the prime minister's post. Thus, 
Shinseito is on the verge of having to choose between going 
ahead with its plan to form a majority group or succumbing to a 
"compromise." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

