<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Poll Finds Hata Favored as Next Prime Minister </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Poll Finds Hata Favored as Next Prime Minister </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1304094194 Tokyo MAINICHI SHIMBUN in Japanese 12 Apr 94 
Morning Edition p 26--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1304094194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo MAINICHI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] On 11 April, MAINICHI SHIMBUN conducted a nationwide 
survey of 250 eligible voters on who should succeed outgoing 
Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa, and found that one-third of 
the respondents want Tsutomu Hata, deputy prime minister and 
foreign minister, to be the next prime minister. 
  The survey was conducted in major cities, such as Tokyo, 
Osaka, Nagoya, Fukuoka, by conducting personal interviews or 
interviews over the phone. In answering "who should be the next 
prime minister?" 78 people (31.2 percent of the respondents) 
supported Hata, 35 (14 percent) Masayoshi Takemura, and 30 (12 
percent) Michio Watanabe as the next prime minister. Lower 
house member Makiko Tanaka and Hokkaido Governor Takahiro 
Yokomichi were also favored as the next prime minister. 
Hokkaido Governor Yokomichi, however, is not eligible to become 
prime minister because he is not a Diet member. 
  As the reason for supporting Hata, a 28-year-old man in 
Tochigi Prefecture said: "He has made a contribution to the 
Hosokawa government. Also, he has been known as Japan's foreign 
minister in other countries. He seems to be an able man." A 
25-year-old woman in Yamaguchi Prefecture said: "Because he has 
strong backing, he will be able to exercise leadership." 
  Takemura ranked second to Hata as a favorite figure to be 
the 
next prime minister. He was popular mainly in the Kansai area 
where he is from. A 47-year-old woman in Osaka said: "He has a 
relatively clean image." A 27-year-old man in Hokkaido also 
said: "He will inherit Mr. Hosokawa's good points." 
  Watanabe was popular among elderly people. Because of his 
career as foreign minister and finance minister, many hoped that 
"Watanabe should carry out Japan's diplomatic policy saying what 
it has to say to the United States, as well as the work to 
reconstruct the economy." 
  Takako Doi and Masaharu Gotoda were also popular because of 
their "clean" image. A 45-year-old woman in Tokyo put her 
expectations on Doi, saying: "I hope that the Diet will take 
the plunge and name Doi as the first female prime minister." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-5625 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas071__a94018" </HT>


