<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Openness in Formation of Next Government Urged </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Openness in Formation of Next Government Urged </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1204084394 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 12 Apr 
94 Morning Edition p 2--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1204084394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Editorial: "The Sovereign People Should Not Be Forgotten </F>
in the Process of Creating New Administration"] 
  [Text] If you look at it as a slapstick comedy, it may be 
quite interesting. But this becomes unbearable when you realize 
that this is the process of creating the next administration. 
While the factional struggle seen in the election of the party 
president, hence, the prime minister, during the Liberal 
Democratic Party [LDP] era was indeed repulsive, the people are 
certainly amazed at the present turmoil among the ruling 
coalition parties, particularly because this came after the 
Hosokawa administration, which upheld "new politics." 
  The ruling parties have not even been able to decide the 
venue for discussions to select the next prime minister. 
Shinseito [Japan Renewal Party], Komeito, and the Japan New 
Party [JNP] insist that the issue should be discussed at the 
"representatives meeting" composed of secretary general-level 
party representatives. On the other hand, leaders of the Social 
Democratic Party of Japan [SDPJ], the Democratic Socialist Party 
[DSP], and Sakigake [Harbinger] assert that this should be 
decided at a "party leaders meeting." Both sides refuse to 
compromise. 
  The leaders of Shinseito, Komeito, and the JNP did not 
attend 
the party leaders meeting initiated by SDPJ Chairman Tomiichi 
Murayama on 11 April. The basic reason is: While Shinseito and 
Komeito want to make the new Diet grouping "Kaikaku" [Reform] 
the center of activities to realign political parties, the SDPJ 
and Sakigake are strongly critical of the idea. 
  Behind the SDPJ and Sakigake's opposition is their antipathy 
to the political style of Ichiro Ozawa, the Shinseito secretary 
general said to be the strong man in the ruling parties. The 
present pattern of balance of forces is exactly the same as that 
during the upheaval relating to the cabinet reshuffle--said to 
be aimed at "getting rid of [Chief Cabinet Secretary Masayoshi] 
Takemura"--last February. Shinseito and its allies are working 
hard to attract former Deputy Prime Minister Michio Watanabe to 
their camp to cut off the SDPJ, Sakigake, and their allies, and 
cooperate with a section of the LDP to maintain their hold on 
the administration. 
  On the other hand, the opposition LDP is aiming at 
recapturing political power by working with the SDPJ and 
Sakigake. Maneuvers to form cross alliances transcending the 
existing political framework of LDP versus non-LDP forces are 
being attempted beneath the surface. Despite the oft-repeated 
claim that "agreement in policy will be the basis of forming a 
government," in reality, top priority is being given to the 
question of how to maneuver to become the ruling party. 
  The Hosokawa administration quickly lost its sense of unity 
after the passage of the political reform bills. Thus, the 
collapse of the government was merely a matter of time all 
along. Yet, the ruling coalition parties simply focused their 
energy on emotional bickering, without preparing fully for the 
creation of a new administration. 
  The same is true for the opposition LDP. It is quite at a 
loss at the sudden collapse of the administration. One cannot 
even feel the LDP's ardor in putting up its president, Yohei 
Kono, as a candidate to recapture the political regime. 
  There are numerous urgent issues facing Japan, such as 
economic stimulation, tax reform, Japan-U.S. relations, and the 
situation on the Korean peninsula. For one thing, the draft 
1994 budget has not even passed deliberations by the lower house 
Budget Committee. Yet, we see no sense of urgency in efforts to 
form a new government. 
  The people will be totally disgusted if the next 
administration is formed solely by the logic of numbers. The 
people should be able to see what the basis of the new 
administration will be, and the process of who makes the 
decision, and where this decision is made. 
  When the Hosokawa administration was inaugurated, the people 
were in the dark as to why it was Hosokawa, and who made the 
decision. The formation of a government is a most vital 
political decision. True political reform precisely consists of 
making this process open for all to see as much as possible. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

