<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hata Comments on Political Situation Prospects </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Hata Comments on Political Situation Prospects </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1404031394 Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database in Japanese 14 
Apr 94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1404031394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By correspondent Izumi Oshima; from NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN 14 </F>
April Morning Edition] 
  [Text] Paris -- Deputy Prime Minister and Foreign Minister 
Tsutomu Hata left Japan on 13 April aboard an exclusive 
government plane for Morocco via Paris, to sign a final Uruguay 
Round accord at ministerial talks. Speaking with a group of 
Japanese reporters aboard the plane about prospects for the 
political situation, Foreign Minister Hata said: "The ruling 
parties are now working on coordinating their opinions in an 
effort to keep their coalition framework intact. I think they 
will soon complete their policy coordination and choose a 
candidate to succeed Prime Minister Hosokawa." In this way, the 
foreign minister predicted that a candidate to succeed Hosokawa 
as prime minister would be chosen early next week. 
  The foreign minister has been mentioned as the most likely 
candidate to succeed Hosokawa as prime minister. Asked by a 
reporter to comment on this, Hata stated: "I have heard about 
it, but I would like to refrain from mentioning the name of the 
person to become prime minister." Touching on talks with U.S. 
Trade Representative Mickey Kantor scheduled to be held on 15 
April, the foreign minister said: "I intend to tell him that a 
change of government in Japan should not set back Japan-U.S. 
relations," and he added: "It is a matter of course for me to 
call on him to resume the stalled Japan-U.S. economic framework 
talks after a new government is inaugurated in Japan." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-5765 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas072__a94009" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-072-A </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  14 April 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bureaucracy Reaction to Hata's Candidacy Viewed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Bureaucracy Reaction to Hata's Candidacy Viewed </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1404084694 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 14 Apr 
Morning Edition p 5 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1404084694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] A feeling of relief is spreading in the central 
government offices in Kasumigaseki at the current moves of the 
ruling coalition parties to select Deputy Prime Minister and 
Foreign Minister Tsutomu Hata as Prime Minister Morihiro 
Hosokawa's successor. This is because the basic framework of 
the ruling coalition parties will be maintained, and the 
political upheaval will probably be resolved sooner than 
expected. 
  Hata, who has served in key cabinet posts, including the 
minister of agriculture, forestry, and fisheries, and the 
minister of finance, also has great credibility. In particular, 
being the incumbent foreign minister, he is familiar with the 
substance of the stalled negotiations between Japan and the 
United States, and has many personal connections in the United 
States. He is widely expected to effect a breakthrough in the 
negotiations. 
  The Ministries of Foreign Affairs [MOFA] and International 
Trade and Industry [MITI] say that Hata "stands firm on issues 
of principle," (MITI) and that "he will speak up to the United 
States whenever necessary." (MOFA) He is admired for 
negotiating with U.S. Trade Representative Mickey Kantor for six 
and one-half hours on the bilateral economic framework talks 
immediately prior to the Japan-U.S. summit meeting in February, 
and insisting that "numerical targets are absolutely 
unacceptable." 
  The Ministry of Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries [MAFF] 
says that, "He has served twice as agriculture minister, and is 
the number one expert on agriculture in the coalition 
government," (according to a senior MAFF official). There is 
widespread expectation on Hata particularly because the MAFF and 
the Prime Minister's Office did not exactly see eye to eye 
during the decision process leading to the partial opening of 
the rice market last year. 
  The Ministry of Finance is elated at the fact that the 
framework of the ruling coalition parties will be basically 
maintained. It believes that not only have prospects for 
starting deliberations on the draft 1994 budget become brighter, 
"some progress can also be excepted in tax reform, although this 
is already a bit behind schedule," (according to the Tax Bureau). 
  However, while expectations are high regarding a 
reconciliation between Japan and the United States, others 
express the concern that: "He is the very person who brought 
about the breakdown in the Japan-U.S. summit meeting; he may 
have some problems when it comes to breaking the current 
deadlock in bilateral relations." Still others are apprehensive 
that with the discord in the ruling parties coming to the 
surface, the policymaking process will be even more arduous. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

