<HT>    "dreas072aa_94001" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-072 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  9 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hosokawa Addresses Trilateral Commission Opening </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Hosokawa Addresses Trilateral Commission Opening </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW0904050494 Tokyo KYODO in English 0441 GMT 9 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0904050494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 9 KYODO -- Outgoing Prime Minister 
Morihiro Hosokawa said Saturday [9 April] the new administration 
will put top priority on economic reforms and deregulation. 
  Addressing the opening session of the Trilateral Commission, 
Hosokawa contended that his government has laid down the ground 
work for deregulation since it came to power last August. 
  The commission is formed by 330 former political and 
business 
leaders from Japan, the United States and Europe to set forth 
proposals on problems of common interest. It is chaired by 
former U.S. Federal Reserve Board Chairman Paul Volcker. 
  The current session, which opened at a Tokyo hotel on 
Saturday, is the commission's 25th general meeting. 
  Hosokawa announced Friday he will step down to take 
responsibility for a stalemate in the Diet over his personal 
problems, including a 100 million yen loan from Sagawa Kyubin, 
the scandal-tainted trucking group. 
  Referring to foreign criticism that Japan's markets are 
closed to imports, Hosokawa said Japan should take positive 
action to open its markets, regarding such criticism as an 
expression of hope for an economic transformation. He said 
promoting economic reform not only benefits the Japanese people 
but is also Japan's international obligation. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

