<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Atomic Industrial Forum Meeting Opens in Japan </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Atomic Industrial Forum Meeting Opens in Japan </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1304012894 Tokyo KYODO in English 0108 GMT 13 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1304012894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Hiroshima, April 13 KYODO -- The Japan Atomic 
Industrial Forum began its annual meeting Wednesday [13 April] 
in Hiroshima, the first time it has been held in the world's 
first atomic-bombed city. 
  The three-day meeting has as its theme "toward a world free 
of nuclear weapons, the role of peaceful use." It will feature 
addresses on Wednesday by Hans Blix, director general of the 
International Atomic Energy Agency, and Pulitzer Prize-winning 
author Richard Rhodes. 
  This year for the first time, at a Wednesday panel 
discussion, the meeting will deal with the problems of 
dismantling nuclear weapons. 
  On Thursday, atomic power advocates are scheduled to meet 
with citizens of Hiroshima and victims of the 1945 atomic 
bombing, including the head of an association of Korean victims 
of the nuclear holocaust, Yi Sil-gun [name as received], for an 
exchange of opinions. 
  Some 1,500 atomic power specialists from Japan and abroad 
are 
expected to take part in the symposium, which has been held 
annually since 1968. 

</TEXT>

