<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Discusses Peaceful Atomic Uses </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Discusses Peaceful Atomic Uses </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1304062994 Tokyo KYODO in English 0557 GMT 13 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1304062994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Hiroshima, April 13 KYODO -- A forum on atomic 
energy started a three-day conference Wednesday [13 April] in 
this atomic-bombed city to discuss the peaceful uses of nuclear 
energy. 
  Takashi Mukaibo, chairman of the Japan Atomic Industrial 
Forum, urged participants to discuss the elimination of nuclear 
weapons and the peaceful uses of atomic energy as the 50th 
anniversary of A-bomb attacks on Hiroshima and Nagasaki is 
approaching. 
  About 1,500 atomic power specialists from Japan and abroad 
are taking part in the 27th annual conference. 
  Around the conference hall in central Hiroshima, about 30 
antinuclear activists protested the meeting. 
  Hans Blix, director general of the International Atomic 
Energy Agency (IAEA), told the meeting that the IAEA will hold a 
special meeting on April 21 and 22 in Vienna to discuss the 
Chernobyl nuclear reactors in Ukraine. 
  Chernobyl was the scene of one of the world's most serious 
nuclear accidents in 1986. Although the nuclear reactor 
involved in the accident has not been operational, two other 
reactors have since been in operation. The Ukrainian government 
decided to continue to operate the two reactors and has asked 
the IAEA to investigate safety. 
  On Thursday, atomic power advocates are scheduled to meet 
with citizens of Hiroshima and victims of the 1945 atomic 
bombing, including the head of an association of Korean victims 
of the nuclear holocaust, Yi Sil-gun [name as received], for an 
exchange of opinions. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

