<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Energy Policy Experts Urge Global Cooperation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Energy Policy Experts Urge Global Cooperation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1404132994 Tokyo KYODO in English 1246 GMT 14 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1404132994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] Kyoto, April 14 KYODO -- The world's energy 
policy experts jointly called for stronger global cooperation 
for stable economic growth and energy policies at a seminar 
under sponsorship of the International Energy Agency (IEA) in 
Kyoto on Thursday [14 April]. 
  The seminar, hosted by Japan to commemorate the 20th 
anniversary of the agency's establishment, gathered some 300 
participants from 26 countries around the world, including four 
nonmember nations of the agency such as Russia. The guests, 
including Bob Hawke, former Australian prime minister, and Brent 
Scowcroft, former U.S. presidential assistant, discussed 
current problems in global security policies in relation to 
energy in the post-Cold War era. 
  They stressed it is important for all countries in the world 
to strengthen cooperation through international organizations 
like the IEA to maintain stable economic growth and energy 
policies. 
  Otto Lambsdorff, former German economic minister, discussed 
the global warming problem stemming from increasing energy use. 
He suggested creation of a tax on carbon dioxide emissions and 
said countries capable of introducing such a tax should do so as 
soon as possible. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

