<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   ROK, Russia Reach Accord on DPRK Loggers </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    ROK, Russia Reach Accord on DPRK Loggers </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1404125494 Seoul YONHAP in English 1235 GMT 14 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1404125494 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, April 14 (YONHAP) -- South Korea and Russia 
on Thursday agreed to handle the issue of North Korean loggers 
in Russia from the approach of humanitarianism and in deference 
to their personal wish. 
  The agreement was reached in a Moscow meeting between 
visiting South Korean Foreign Minister Han Sung-chu and his 
Russian counterpart, Andrey Kozyrev. 
  The two ministers also discussed the question of President 
Kim Yong-sam's planned visit to Moscow in June. 
  Vice Foreign Minister Hong Sun-yong said in Seoul that 
during 
the meeting, Minister Han asked Kozyrev to give positive 
assistance in case those North Korean loggers who had escaped 
Pyongyang-run logging yards in Siberia wish to come to South 
Korea. 
  "Minister Han also stressed that escaped North Korean 
loggers 
should not be repatriated to North Korea against their will, 
asking Russia to see to it they remain under Russia's legal 
protection," Hong said. 
  The vice minister said Minister Kozyrev made it clear that 
Russia will positively cooperate in having North Korean loggers 
lawfully go to a country or countries of their choice. 
  They also agreed on the need to obtain cooperation from the 
United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) so as to 
buttress the fairness and objectivity of the way North Korean 
loggers will be handled. 
  On President Kim's official visit to Russia, the two 
ministers in effect confirmed the time of his visit, June this 
year, and discussed the agenda topics of a Korea-Russia summit 
meeting to be held during kim's visit, Vice Minister Hong said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

