<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   PRC's Qian Qichen Cited on DPRK Issue Progress </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    PRC's Qian Qichen Cited on DPRK Issue Progress </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1404012194 Seoul YONHAP in English 0112 GMT 14 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1404012194 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 14 (YONHAP) -- Chinese Foreign Minister 
Qian Qichen, saying the North Korean nuclear issue is heading in 
the right direction, asserted the problem should be resolved 
through dialogue, the TOKYO SHIMBUN reported Thursday. 
  Qian made the remark in an interview with the newspapers's 
publisher, Kato Kiichiro, at the official Chinese guest house in 
Beijing. 
  Qian also said it is understandable that Pyongyang rejected 
a 
UN Security Council presidential statement because North Korea 
opposes the council taking up the nuclear matter. The 
presidential statement, adopted unanimously by the council, 
urges North Korea to allow outside inspections of its nuclear 
facilities. 
  The North Korean nuclear impasse, nevertheless, is "moving 
in 
the right direction bit by bit," Qian was quoted as saying. 
  He said China favors talks through three channels -- between 
North Korea and the United States, between North and South Korea 
and between North Korea and the International Atomic Energy 
Agency (IAEA). 
  Qian said China pushed the Security Council president's 
statement, which has no binding power, since it is against the 
United Nations handling the issue. 
  Asked whether North Korea had nuclear bombs, Qian said he 
could not be sure. This seemed to indicate a slight change in 
China's previous position that North Korea has neither the 
intention nor the ability to develop nuclear weapons, the TOKYO 
SHIMBUN reported. 

</TEXT>

