<H3> <TI>   Nissan Decides on U.S. Production of Forklifts </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Nissan Decides on U.S. Production of Forklifts </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1404135594 Tokyo KYODO in English 1307 GMT 14 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1404135594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 14 KYODO -- Nissan Motor Co. said 
Thursday [14 April] that one of its U.S. subsidiaries will 
start production of Nissan electric forklifts in the second half 
of 1995. 
  Nissan Forklift Corp., North America (NFC), based in 
Marengo, 
Illinois, made the decision in order to further advance 
localization as well as to help shorten delivery time and cut 
production costs, the second-largest Japanese automaker said. 
  NFC now produces internal-combustion-powered forklifts 
mainly 
for the North American market. It also makes electric forklifts 
under the Barrett brand name. 
  NFC is owned 2 percent by Nissan, 88 percent by a Nissan 
subsidiary, Nissan Industrial Equipment Co., and the remaining 
10 percent by Marubeni Corp., a giant Japanese trading house. 

</TEXT>

