<H3> <TI>   Saito: DPRK Solution Sought Through Dialogue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Saito: DPRK Solution Sought Through Dialogue </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1404150594 Tokyo KYODO in English 1446 GMT 14 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1404150594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 14 KYODO -- The head of the U.N. 
nuclear monitoring agency predicts the problem of North Korea's 
alleged development of nuclear weapons may be brought up again 
at the U.N. Security Council if there is no progress on the 
issue by early May, a top Japanese Foreign Ministry official 
said Thursday [14 April]. 
  Hans Blix, director general of the International Atomic 
Energy Agency (IAEA), made the remark in a meeting with Vice 
Foreign Minister Kunihiko Saito, the official said. 
  Saito told Blix that Japan wants to seek a solution to the 
North Korean nuclear problem through dialogue, he said. 
  The official, speaking on condition of anonymity, declined 
to 
elaborate on the meeting. 
  Blix is in Japan to attend an annual meeting in Hiroshima of 
the Japan Atomic Industrial Forum. 
  He said in Hiroshima that the IAEA has sent a letter to 
North 
Korea asking that inspectors be allowed access to a 
radiochemical laboratory but that Pyongyang has not responded 
yet. 
  IAEA inspectors were allowed into North Korea in March for 
their first look at nuclear facilities there in more than a year. 
  But they were unable to determine if radioactive materials 
had been diverted to military purposes because North Korea 
blocked the inspectors from a key laboratory. 
  North Korea says its nuclear program is peaceful. 

</TEXT>

