<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Fukuoka, April 14 KYODO -- Japanese and South 
Korean business executives opened a two-day meeting Thursday [14 
April] on Japan's westernmost main island of Kyushu to discuss 
economic cooperation between the two countries. 
  About 300 executives are attending the 26th annual joint 
meeting of the private Japan-Korea Economic Committee and its 
South Korean counterpart at a Fukuoka hotel. 
  Nobuya Hagura, chairman of the Japan-Korea Economic 
Association and adviser to Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank, and Pak 
Yong-hak, chairman of its South Korean counterpart, made opening 
speeches at the meeting, the first to be held in Kyushu. 
  The meeting will close Friday, when it issues a joint 
statement after holding subcommittee sessions on trade, 
industrial cooperation and various exchanges between the two 
countries. 

