<H3> <TI>   Saito Says G-7 Talks To Focus on Jobs, Growth </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Saito Says G-7 Talks To Focus on Jobs, Growth </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1404091494 Tokyo KYODO in English 0902 GMT 14 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1404091494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 14 KYODO -- World growth and job 
problems will top discussions at a series of international 
financial meetings slated later this month in Washington, a 
senior Finance Ministry official said Thursday [14 April]. 
  The meetings will "center on the issues of still high 
unemployment among Group of Seven (G-7) industrial nations and 
on stable world growth, particularly with European nations still 
not in good shape," Vice Finance Minister Jiro Saito told a news 
meeting. 
  A spate of international gatherings of financial leaders are 
scheduled in Washington late this month, led by the semiannual 
meetings of the International Monetary Fund (IMF) Interim 
Committee, the Joint Development Committee of the IMF and the 
World Bank. 
  An international financial source said finance ministers and 
central bankers from the G-7 nations are expected to meet April 
24 before the gatherings. 
  The G-7 nations are Britain, Canada, France, Germany, Italy, 
Japan and the United States. 
  Saito said he is yet not certain about a bilateral meeting 
between Finance Minister Hirohisa Fujii and U.S. Treasury 
Secretary Lloyd Bentsen. 

</TEXT>

