<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Differences Over Hosokawa's Successor Continue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Differences Over Hosokawa's Successor Continue </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Coalition Remains Divided </H4>

<F P=102> OW1404141994 Tokyo KYODO in English 1358 GMT 14 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1404141994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 14 KYODO -- A lingering row within the 
governing coalition on Thursday [14 April] continued the 
stalemate in talks over future policies and the choice of a 
successor to outgoing Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa. 
  Leaders of three of the seven coalition parties met Thursday 
evening and agreed not to endorse a package of proposals adopted 
at an earlier meeting of the coalition's decision-making caucus 
made up of secretaries general, coalition officials said. 
  The three parties are the Social Democratic Party (SDP), the 
largest coalition contingent, and its two allies -- the 
Democratic Socialist Party (DSP) and new party Sakigake 
[Harbinger]. 
  At the gathering of the coalition executives, which Sakigake 
boycotted, they shared the view that the eight-month-old 
alliance might collapse if its components reject the agreement, 
the officials said. 
  The agreement calls on all top leaders of coalition parties 
to decide by themselves to convene a meeting to discuss the 
makeup of a new coalition government and the selection of a 
candidate to replace Hosokawa, the officials said. 
  It also included an accord to resume talks on policy matters 
toward establishment of the next administration and an appeal 
for Sakigake, a tiny component of the ruling union, to return to 
the negotiating table, they said. 
  Sakigake, led by Chief Cabinet Secretary Masayoshi Takemura, 
convened a general meeting Thursday evening of all its 15 House 
of Representatives members, who unanimously agreed to reject the 
coalition accord on the reopening of policy talks, party 
officials said. 
  Sakigake has contended that top party leaders, and not the 
secretaries general-level representatives, should contemplate a 
combination of political parties that would comprise the new 
coalition government and find a successor to Hosokawa. 
  It is widely believed the party's stance is intended to 
prevent the coalition's main strategist Ichiro Ozawa, secretary 
general of Shinseito (Japan Renewal Party), and his ally, 
Komeito Secretary General Yuichi Ichikawa, from dominating 
policy-making on the choice of a new premier. 
  Under the Hosokawa administration, the personal rivalry 
between Ozawa and Takemura flared up many times over such key 
policy issues as political reform, the partial opening of 
Japan's rice market, and Hosokawa's abortive attempts to impose 
a new value-added tax called the "National Welfare Tax" and 
reshuffle the cabinet. 
  In a three-way meeting Thursday morning, SDP Chairman 
Tomiichi Murayama, DSP Chairman Keigo Ouchi and Sakigake's 
Takemura agreed that a forum of all coalition heads should seek 
a breakthrough in the selection process. 
  The three parties earlier called for a meeting of the 
coalition leaders, but Shinseito, Komeito and Hosokawa's Japan 
New Party (JNP) rejected the appeal. 
  Following rejection of the package by the three coalition 
heads and Sakigake, the deputy chiefs met twice and agreed to 
allow the SDP and the DSP to take their time to fine-tune 
opinions within the parties, coalition officials said. 
  The coalition executives will gather again on Friday 
afternoon, the officials said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-5796 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas072_a_94010" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-072 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  14 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Differences Over Hosokawa's Successor Continue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Differences Over Hosokawa's Successor Continue </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Miyazawa Faction Supports Kono </H4>

<F P=102> OW1404125794 Tokyo KYODO in English 1203 GMT 14 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1404125794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 14 KYODO -- Liberal Democratic Party 
(LDP) President Yohei Kono will meet Michio Watanabe, an LDP 
faction leader and former foreign minister, on Friday [15 April] 
to ask him not to run for the premiership to avoid splitting the 
largest opposition party, LDP sources said Thursday. 
  Kono will visit the faction office of Watanabe at 4 P.M. 
[0700 GMT] Friday, they said. 
  Kono vowed Tuesday to run in a prime ministerial election in 
the Diet for the successor to outgoing Prime Minister Morihiro 
Hosokawa, who last Friday announced his resignation. 
  Watanabe is eager to be prime minister and had rejected 
Kono's request for face-to-face talks. 
  Executive members of his faction met Wednesday and agreed to 
lobby other LDP members by seeking their signatures endorsing 
Watanabe as the next premier, faction sources said. Nearly 100 
signatures have been collected, a senior faction executive said. 
  Watanabe faction executives affirmed their opinions that the 
LDP president must not necessarily be the party's candidate for 
prime minister, and that a government with large alliances of 
ruling and opposition camps is needed to break through the 
political turmoil following Hosokawa's announcement, they said. 
  Members of an LDP faction led by former Prime Minister 
Kiichi 
Miyazawa agreed Thursday to back Kono as the sole LDP candidate 
for the premiership, faction sources said. Kono had belonged to 
the Miyazawa faction until he became LDP president last July. 
  The Miyazawa faction decided to set up an election campaign 
office for Kono in a Tokyo hotel in case Watanabe does not give 
up his candidacy and to seek support from other parties' 
members, the sources said. 
  In three other factions -- led respectively by former 
Transport Minister Hiroshi Mitsuzuka, former Chief Cabinet 
Secretary Keizo Obuchi and former State Minister Toshio Komoto 
-- members generally fear a party split-up and hope Kono and 
Watanabe will peacefully resolve the candidacy issue through 
talks, faction sources said. 
  Watanabe emerged earlier this week as a prime ministerial 
candidate after a feud within the ruling coalition threatened to 
split the government, weakening the chances of front-runner 
Foreign Minister Tsutomu Hata being named Hosokawa's successor. 
  But on Tuesday, the coalition, which was on the verge of 
collapse, moved to maintain the current framework of the 
government, once again strengthening Hata's hand. 
  However, a senior member of Watanabe's faction said there is 
still hope Watanabe will be named prime minister because the 
ruling coalition parties have failed to mend wounds within the 
shaky alliance and band together to support Hata. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

