<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Differences Over Hosokawa's Successor Continue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Differences Over Hosokawa's Successor Continue </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Lower House Members Support Hata </H4>

<F P=102> OW1404145994 Tokyo KYODO in English 1435 GMT 14 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1404145994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 14 KYODO -- Foreign Minister and 
Shinseito [Japan Renewal Party] head Tsutomu Hata garnered the 
biggest support as Japan's next prime minister among more than 
130 House of Representatives members in a poll released Thursday 
[14 April]. 
  Nippon Broadcasting System Corp., a Tokyo radio station, 
said 
it conducted the survey on Wednesday and Thursday, covering all 
the 508 lower house members, to ask who is best as Japan's next 
leader. Of them, 132 lawmakers or 26 percent responded by fax. 
  The largest number, 61 respondents, picked Hata, followed by 
29 who supported Yohei Kono, president of the main opposition 
Liberal Democratic Party (LDP), 13 for Tetsuzo Fuwa, presidium 
chairman of the opposition Japanese Communist Party, and 10 for 
former Foreign Minister Michio Watanabe of the LDP, they said. 
  Hata, head of Shinseito, a core component in the seven-party 
coalition, is already thought to be the most likely candidate to 
succeed Hosokawa. 
  Hata gained support from members of ruling parties including 
the Social Democratic Party, Shinseito, Komeito [Clean 
Government Party] and the Japan New Party, but Kono and Fuwa 
were backed only by members of their parties, the poll showed. 
  Those who backed Hata said he is appropriate for premiership 
because he has served in many ministerial posts, is eager for 
political reform and has a fine character, it said. 
  Supporters for Kono said he should be premier because he is 
head of the largest single party in the Diet and because he says 
Japan should keep its war-renouncing constitution. 
  Those who cited Watanabe said he has leadership skills and 
is 
knowledgeable about the economy. 

</TEXT>

