<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Differences Over Hosokawa's Successor Continue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Differences Over Hosokawa's Successor Continue </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Watanabe on `Strong Interest' </H4>

<F P=102> OW1404050794 Tokyo KYODO in English 0501 GMT 14 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1404050794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 14 KYODO -- Former Foreign Minister 
Michio Watanabe, an influential figure in the top opposition 
Liberal Democratic Party (LDP), on Thursday reaffirmed his 
strong interest in succeeding outgoing Prime Minister Morihiro 
Hosokawa. 
  "I'm watching whether (the ruling coalition parties) will be 
able to adjust their policies while sticking to the coalition 
framework," Watanabe told reporters. 
  He also said he wanted to appeal to the people to rescue the 
country from difficulties, and said party or faction ambitions 
should be put aside to this end. 
  On possible talks with LDP President Yohei Kono, who has 
vowed to run in the premiership race in the Diet as the party's 
candidate, Watanabe reacted reluctantly, saying "now is not the 
time to meet with him." 
  Watanabe's bid to become prime minister has brought the LDP 
to the verge of a major split, political sources said. 
  Watanabe's faction, which is beefing up its campaign to 
promote their leader as a successor to Hosokawa, meanwhile has 
rallied some 50 House of Representatives lawmakers of the LDP, 
including 36 of its 45 faction members, behind Watanabe, faction 
sources said. 
  The faction, the fourth largest among the LDP's five 
factions, is aiming to collect signatures from some 100 LDP 
members of the powerful lower house, supporting a call for 
faction members to back Watanabe, they said. 
  The leading opposition party holds 219 seats in the 
511-member lower chamber. 
  Shinseito and Komeito, two of the key parties in the ruling 
coalition, once deemed Watanabe as the leader of a possible new 
coalition grouping, because of his political savvy and 
influence, political sources said. 
  Although Foreign Minister Tsutomu Hata, who heads Shinseito, 
has emerged as the most likely successor to Hosokawa, the seven 
ruling coalition parties remain divided over the process by 
which a new premier will be selected. 
  Hosokawa announced his resignation last Friday over 
financial 
improprieties. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

