<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Sakigake Threatens To Leave Ruling Coalition </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Sakigake Threatens To Leave Ruling Coalition </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1404151994 Tokyo KYODO in English 1510 GMT 14 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1404151994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 14 KYODO -- New party Sakigake 
[Harbinger Party] leader Masayoshi Takemura threatened Thursday 
[14 April] to break away from the eight-month-old ruling 
coalition. 
  Takemura, appearing on TV ASAHI's "News Station" program, 
said, "nowadays, some politicians say the coalition should expel 
Sakigake or the Social Democratic Party (SDP), so our party has 
come to be regarded as fragile." 
  "Our party does not have an unconditional desire to remain 
in 
the government," whatever humiliation it may suffer, said 
Takemura, who has exerted his influence as the chief cabinet 
secretary under Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa, who announced 
last Friday he is resigning. 
  "Because we have that resolve (to splinter if necessary), we 
are now speaking our mind," said Takemura, leader of a small 
coalition component formed by 15 members of the 511-seat House 
of Representatives. 
  But Takemura hinted that if the coalition's majority group 
led by Shinseito [Japan Renewal Party] stop trying to 
marginalize him, Sakigake is ready to continue to put its weight 
behind the coalition to keep it in power. 
  His comments came as the three-way caucus of Sakigake, the 
SDP and the Democratic Socialist Party (DSP) is confronting the 
Shinseito-led camp that includes Komeito [Clean Government 
Party] and Hosokawa's Japan New Party over who should be the 
next premier. 
  Takemura has reportedly been squabbling with Shinseito 
Secretary General Ichiro Ozawa, who is regarded as the 
coalition's most influential politician, over who should take 
the role of the behind-the-scenes fixer in deciding the course 
of the coalition government. 
  "I believe neither our side nor their camp think we may 
allow 
the coalition to dissolve," Takemura said. 
  "I do not want to allow the current combination of coalition 
parties to crumble, either," he said. "I do not dislike Mr. 
Ozawa and I believe we can get along with each other." 
  "However, his repentance and readiness to restart is 
necessary," Takemura said. 

</TEXT>

