<H3> <TI>   Murayama Opposes Kubo Plan on Reconciliation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Murayama Opposes Kubo Plan on Reconciliation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1404152794 Tokyo KYODO in English 1520 GMT 14 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1404152794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 15 KYODO -- The leader of the 
coalition's largest party on Thursday [14 April] balked at a 
proposal by the party's No. 2 man to give the authority to 
discuss how to reconcile intraparty policy differences to the 
coalition's deputy chiefs. 
  Social Democratic Party (SDP) [Social Democratic Party of 
Japan -- SDPJ] Chairman Tomiichi Murayama told reporters, "I can 
never approve of that proposal" by SDP Secretary General Wataru 
Kubo to allow the secretaries general of the coalition to hold 
substantial discussion on narrowing an intraparty gulf over key 
policies, such as defense and diplomacy. 
  Kubo advanced the proposal as the chairman of get-togethers 
of the deputy chiefs of the coalition partners. 
  Murayama's remark came a day after key coalition strategist 
Ichiro Ozawa, secretary general of the core coalition party 
Shinseito [Japan Renewal party], called for bridging 
intracoalition gaps over four key policy fields, including 
Japan's stand on the suspected North Korean nuclear weapons 
program. 
  The other three fields are Japan's tax system reform, basic 
defense and foreign policies as well as administrative reform 
combined with deregulation. 
  Murayama dismissed the rumors rift with Kubo, saying the SDP 
secretary general merely "advanced the proposal as the chairman 
of meetings of the secretaries general as a tentative step." 
  "There are no differences between me and Mr. Kubo," Murayama 
said. 
  Ozawa and Kubo respectively put forward calls for 
reconciling 
the intra-alliance gaps after Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa's 
seven-party alliance went through various crises and turbulence 
due to policy differences over the past eight months. 

</TEXT>

