<H3> <TI>   Court Rejects Nakamura Bail Appeal Third Time </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Court Rejects Nakamura Bail Appeal Third Time </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1404112494 Tokyo KYODO in English 1049 GMT 14 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1404112494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 14 KYODO -- The Tokyo District Court 
rejected Thursday [14 April] an appeal from former Construction 
Minister Kishiro Nakamura against a judge's decision Wednesday 
not to release him on bail, Nakamura's defense attorneys said. 
  The three-judge panel acted on an appeal from Nakamura who 
had asked for bail so he can take part in a Diet vote to pick a 
successor to Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa, who announced his 
resignation last Friday. But no date has been set for the Diet 
vote yet. 
  Nakamura, 45, an independent member of the House of 
Representatives, has been detained at the Tokyo detention house 
since mid-March after prosecutors arrested him on suspicion of 
taking a 10 million yen bribe from leading general contractor 
Kajima Corp. 
  Prosecutors indicted Nakamura on April 1 on charges of 
taking 
the bribe on January 13, 1992, from Shinji Kiyoyama, then vice 
president of Kajima. 
  The Tokyo District Court did not state its reasons for the 
latest rejection. 
  Nakamura's first bail application was dismissed last Tuesday 
on the grounds he might destroy evidence. 
  Nakamura's latest appeal was a "junkoku" appeal which can be 
filed with a three-judge panel at a district court. It is a 
legal recourse available under the Code of Criminal Procedure 
when the defense claims it is dissatisfied with a decision by a 
single judge. 
  Nakamura is the sole Diet member implicated in connection 
with an influence-peddling scandal surrounding the country's 
leading construction contractors. 
  He quit the Liberal Democratic Party just before his arrest 
and is currently an independent member of the lower house. 
  If found guilty, Nakamura could face up to five years in 
prison, according to the penal code. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

