<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Shirai on Admonishing Broadcasting Bureau Chief </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Shirai on Admonishing Broadcasting Bureau Chief </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1404140394 Tokyo KYODO in English 1343 GMT 14 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1404140394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 14 KYODO -- Futoshi Shirai, 
administrative vice minister of posts and telecommunications, 
said Thursday [14 April] he will admonish the ministry's 
broadcasting bureau chief for inadvertent remarks on action that 
might be taken against telecasting companies which made 
erroneous forecasts of poll results in last July's general 
election. Shirai made the remark in a press conference, 
commenting on what was said by Akimasa Egawa in a press 
conference Monday. 
  The bureau chief told the press some broadcasting companies 
had reported that certain candidates were considered safe bets 
for election, but that several of them were found later to have 
been unsuccessful. 
  Egawa said some administrative action, such as admonition, 
verbal or in writing, will be given to such companies. 
  The vice minister said his ministry will decide whether or 
not to ask the companies to be more careful in making forecasts 
while giving due consideration to freedom in editing programs. 

</TEXT>

