<H3> <TI>   Steel Output Falls 1.9 Percent in FY `93 </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Steel Output Falls 1.9 Percent in FY `93 </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1404060094 Tokyo KYODO in English 0554 GMT 14 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1404060094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 14 KYODO -- Japan's crude steel 
production fell below 100 million tons in fiscal 1993, ended 
March 31, for the second year in a row, the Japan Iron and Steel 
Federation said Thursday [14 April]. 
  Japanese steelmakers turned out a total of 97.11 million 
tons 
of crude steel, a 1.9 percent fall from the previous year and 
the smallest volume since fiscal 1986, it said in a report 
reflecting the weak national economy. 
  In March alone, crude steel production fell for the sixth 
straight month of year-to-year declines, sliding 9.8 percent 
from a year earlier to 7.75 million tons, it said. 
  The March production volume represents an increase of 7.1 
percent from the month before, although March was the fifth 
consecutive month in which crude steel output fell below 8 
million tons. 
  Crude steel production is viewed as a key economic 
indicator, 
as steel products are used for a variety of industrial goods 
ranging from autos to machinery. 

</TEXT>

