<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Discusses U.S. Talks, Ties </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Discusses U.S. Talks, Ties </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1304153394 Pyongyang KCNA in English 1524 GMT 13 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1304153394 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Pyongyang, April 13 (KCNA) -- Kim Yong-sun, 
secretary of the Central Committee of the Workers' Party of 
Korea and chairman of the Reunification Policy Committee of the 
Supreme People's Assembly [SPA] of the Democratic People's 
Republic of Korea, at the talks held here today between 
officials of the SPA Reunification Policy Committee and former 
heads of state and government and politicians of different 
countries, informed the guests of the situation of Korea and the 
DPRK's stand toward national reunification and the DPRK-U.S. 
relations and its foreign policy. 
  "Our singlehearted unity of the whole society is the most 
valuable wealth of ours and nothing can break it," he said. 
  Noting that a powerful independent national economy had been 
built in the DPRK, he said: 
  "Some people are now threatening to impose `economic 
blockade' on us. But it does not work with us." 
  "Powerful self-defence capacities have been built up with 
the 
chuche idea applied in the field of national defence," he said, 
and added: 
  "The nature of our-style socialism centred on the popular 
masses in which the chuche idea has been applied is peace. But, 
it is ready to cope with the situation when our sovereignty is 
violated or the supreme interests of the country encroached on. 
  "It is attributable entirely to the great ideology and the 
great leadership that everything is going well in our country. 
  "The leader devotes himself to the popular masses and the 
latter remains faithful to the former. So, it is natural that 
everything is going well. It is the steel-like faith of our 
people that they will surely win as they are guided by Comrade 
Kim Chong-il, supreme commander." 
  Kim Yong-sun continued: 
  "We constantly maintain that the question of national 
reunification should be solved independently and peacefully on 
the principle of great national unity. 
  "If the national reunification question is to be resolved, 
many issues must be solved. First of all, peace must be ensured 
on the Korean peninsula. To this end, disarmament must be 
achieved and problems solved between the DPRK and the United 
States." 
  Recalling that the United States had reversed the agreed 
conclusions reached at the DPRK-U.S. talks and the New York 
contacts and aggravated the situation in a bid to stifle the 
DPRK under the pretext of the "nuclear suspicion," he said: 
  "We want to solve the issue through negotiations with the 
United States with patience. If the United States persistently 
sought a solution with strength, however, we will be left with 
no other choice but to do our own way. 
  "It will be favourable to the United States itself that it 
look squarely at the world tending toward diversification and 
the changing situation and act with discretion. 
  "The basic idea of the foreign policy of our party and the 
DPRK Government is independence, peace and friendship. We will 
as ever consistently implement this policy." 
  The talks proceeded in an atmosphere of mutual 
understanding. 

</TEXT>

