<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Takemura Denies DPRK Ties Impede Policymaking </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Takemura Denies DPRK Ties Impede Policymaking </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1304032194 Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database in Japanese 13 
Apr 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1304032194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN 13 April Morning Edition] </F>
  [Text] At a news conference on the afternoon of 12 April, 
Chief Cabinet Secretary Masayoshi Takemura (head of Sakigake) 
commented on reports that his close relations with North Korea 
may impede the Japanese Government's policymaking on the DPRK's 
(North Korea) suspected development of nuclear arms. He denied 
such reports, saying: "It is true I am vice chairman of the 
Japan-North Korea Parliamentary Union, and I was also a member 
of (former Liberal Democratic Party Vice President Shin) 
Kanemaru's delegation which visited North Korea. However, this 
does not constitute any basis for saying I have suspicious 
relations with North Korea." Regarding reports that some U.S. 
Government officials are beginning to regard Takemura as the 
"North Korean connection" in the Japanese Government, Takemura 
said: "I have never heard of such a connection." 

</TEXT>

