<H3> <TI>   Mahathir's Official Visit Continues </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Mahathir's Official Visit Continues </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Meets Ranariddh, Hun Sen </H4>

<F P=102> BK1404121594 Kuala Lumpur BERNAMA in English 1034 GMT 14 Apr 
94 </F>

<F P=103> BK1404121594 </F>
<F P=104>  Kuala Lumpur BERNAMA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Abdul Rahman Sulaiman] </F>
  [Text] Phnom Penh, April 14 (OANA-BERNAMA) -- Dr. Mahathir 
Mohamed Thursday met with Cambodia's Co-Prime Ministers Prince 
Norodom Ranaridh and Hun Sen for discussions to further enhance 
the growth of ties between the two countries. 
  The prime minister was accompanied by Foreign Minister 
Abdullah Ahmad Badawi, Primary Industries Minister Dr. Lim Keng 
Yaik and other officials to the talks held at the Cambodian 
prime ministers' office. 
  Cambodia, which is undergoing economic rehabilitation and 
reconstruction following the restoration of peace and stability, 
is said to be keen to emulate Malaysia's economic success as 
well as that of its other ASEAN neighbours. 
  Dr. Mahathir, here for a two-day official visit at the 
invitation of the Cambodian Government, arrived Thursday morning 
together with a 23-member official delegation. 
  Also with him was his wife Dr. Siti Hasmah Mohamed Ali and 
69 
Malaysian businessmen. 
  The business delegation, led by Arab Malaysia Merchant Bank 
Berhad [Limited] executive chairman Azman Hashim, is here to 
further explore business and investment opportunities in this 
former socialist state whose potentials are still largely 
untapped. 
  Despite Thursday being the Cambodian new year and public 
holiday here, the prime minister and his entourage were given a 
rousing welcome on arrival at the Pochentong International 
Airport, near here. 
  Dr. Mahathir and Dr. Siti Hasmah were received by First 
Prime 
Minister Prince Ranariddh and his wife. 
  Later, the prime minister had an audience with King Norodom 
Sihanouk who had just returned home from medical treatment 
abroad specially to welcome the Malaysian leader. 

</TEXT>

