<F P=100> SOUTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Cambodia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Press Reports on Fighting in Pailin Continue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Press Reports on Fighting in Pailin Continue </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Division Commander Flees to Thailand </H4>

<F P=102> BK1504032994 (Clandestine) Voice of the Great National Union 
Front of Cambodia in Cambodian 2330 GMT 14 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK1504032994 </F>
<F P=104>  (Clandestine) Voice of the Great National Union 
Front of Cambodia </F>

<F P=105>  Cambodian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] According to a report from the Pailin battlefield, 
Ritthi, the commander and many officers and soldiers of the 
puppet 6th Division, routed in battle, have fled into Thai 
territory. 
  1. On 12 April, we attacked the enemy troops west of Pailin 
and at Boeng Pralit, thus blocking the stretches of road within 
the perimeter of Pailin to the northern, southern, and eastern 
parts. We smashed the invading forces into bits and launched 
infantry attacks and shelling on their general command post at 
Boeng Pralit, killing or wounding many of them. Many others 
fled in disarray. 
  2. These escapees are 6th Division commander Ritthi and 60 
officers and soldiers. Many of them were wounded. Having been 
constantly attacked and pressured by the National Army of 
Democratic Kampuchea, they fled into Thai territory. 
  On 12 April, they fled in great alarm onto Thai soil, 
carrying weapons but wearing only shorts. The local people 
crowded around this General (Ritthi), because it is strange to 
see this general in such a position in spite of the earlier 
propaganda by the Phnom Penh ringleaders and some Western 
foreigners claiming that Pailin was under Phnom Penh control. 

</TEXT>

