<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Banks Complete Swapping of Brazilian Debt </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Banks Complete Swapping of Brazilian Debt </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1504064794 Tokyo KYODO in English 0546 GMT 15 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1504064794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 15 KYODO -- Japanese banks on Friday 
[15 April] completed swapping 650 billion yen worth of loans to 
Brazil for equities to restructure the debt, banking officials 
said. 
  The so-called Brady bonds will be listed in Europe and most 
of the banks are expected to sell them immediately, the 
officials said. 
  The officials said the bonds are expected to be sold for a 
total of 350 billion yen. This will leave the banks with losses 
of 300 billion yen which they expect to liquidate in closing 
their midterm books at the end of September. 
  The plan is part of the Brady initiative launched in 1989 by 
former U.S. Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady. 
  Under the initiative, creditor banks, after discounting 
credit, swap loans to Latin American countries for bonds issued 
by the debtor nations. 
  Banks have previously liquidated bad loans to Mexico, 
Venezuela and Argentina using a similar method. The Brazilian 
scheme wraps up the initiative, the officials said. 

</TEXT>

