<H3> <TI>   Reiterates Plan To Form Party </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Reiterates Plan To Form Party </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1504035394 Tokyo KYODO in English 0340 GMT 15 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1504035394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 15 KYODO -- Former Deputy Premier and 
Foreign Minister Michio Watanabe reiterated a wish Friday to run 
for a prime ministerial election, suggesting forming a new 
political party by breaking away from the main opposition 
Liberal Democratic Party (LDP). 
  Watanabe told reporters ahead of a meeting with LDP 
President 
Yohei Kono on Friday afternoon that "I am groping for (a way) to 
realize our ideas and principles." 
  But Watanabe did not give a specific answer to a question of 
whether he has already decided to leave the LDP and set up a new 
party, saying, "now is not the time to declare it." 
  Asked when he will make an official announcement of his 
candidacy, Watanabe said, "I have to talk with my party's 
colleagues before speaking out on a final decision." 
  Kono is to meet with Watanabe in a last-ditch effort to 
settle on a sole LDP candidate for the prime ministerial 
election. 
  Political sources said Watanabe's remarks suggest he will 
reject Kono's request for giving up his candidacy, which may 
lead to a breakup of the LDP. 
  Although ousted from its 38-year grip on power last August 
by 
the coalition government led by Prime Minister Morihiro 
Hosokawa, the LDP remains the largest force in the Diet. 
  Former Prime Minister Yasuhiro Nakasone, once a mentor of 
Watanabe as the former head of his faction, denied the 
possibility of Watanabe forming a new political party, saying 
that such a move "is not imminent." 

</TEXT>

