<H3> <TI>   Five Liberal Democratic Party Members Resign </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Five Liberal Democratic Party Members Resign </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1504050794 Tokyo KYODO in English 0448 GMT 15 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1504050794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 15 KYODO -- Five House of 
Representatives members of the main opposition Liberal 
Democratic Party (LDP) bolted the party and another five members 
plan to quit the party, LDP sources said Friday. 
  The move came amid reports that former Foreign Minister 
Michio Watanabe has decided to break away from the LDP, launch a 
new party and vie to succeed outgoing Prime Minister Morihiro 
Hosokawa. 
  Michihiko Kano, Masahiko Kitagawa, Goji Sakamoto, Takao Sato 
and Teruhiko Mashiko, members of a faction led by former Trade 
Minister Hiroshi Mitsuzuka, submitted letters of resignation to 
the LDP leadership, party officials said. 
  Seiichi Ota, Shokei Arai, Koji Kakizawa, Taku Yamamoto and 
Shizuo Sato also plan to quit the party, the party sources said. 
  Earlier in the day LDP Secretary General Yoshiro Mori told a 
news conference the LDP should maintain unity over the choice of 
its candidate for the premiership. 
  "In any event, the best way for our party to return to power 
is to pull together and remain united," Mori said. 
  Mori said he will closely monitor a meeting between LDP 
President Yohei Kono and Watanabe on Friday afternoon. 
  Kono is expected to ask Watanabe not to run for the 
premiership in order to avoid a major split of the LDP. 
  Kano told reporters his group will form a new party aimed at 
bringing about a realignment of political parties. Kano's group 
is expected to team up with Shinseito [Japan Renewal Party], a 
key party in the coalition. Ota and four others are members of 
a suprafaction policy study group called "liberals," which has 
urged Watanabe to run for the premiership. 

</TEXT>

