<H3> <TI>   JNP, DSP Decide To Form Policy Study Group </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    JNP, DSP Decide To Form Policy Study Group </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1504111794 Tokyo KYODO in English 1053 GMT 15 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1504111794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 15 KYODO -- The Japan New Party (JNP) 
and the Democratic Socialist Party (DSP), two of the seven 
parties in the ruling coalition, will form a joint policy study 
group as early as the end of this month, party sources said 
Friday [15 April]. 
  At the beginning of next week, Muneaki Samejima, deputy 
secretary general of the JNP, and Kansei Nakano, the DSP's 
policy board chairman, will begin preparing for the forum to 
study policies to achieve a better quality of life for Japanese 
people, they said. 
  The alliance will take over a suspended JNP plan to ask 
other 
coalition parties to join "Kaikaku (Reform)," the JNP's 
parliamentary group in the House of Representatives, the sources 
said. 
  The launching of the group, however, means that the DSP will 
join the reform in the future, they said. 
  The JNP, led by outgoing Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa, 
disbanded a parliamentary alliance with new party Sakigake 
(Harbinger) led by Chief Cabinet Secretary Masayoshi Takemura 
shortly after he announced his resignation on April 8. 
  It then formed the reform with two United Social Democratic 
Party members including Science and Technology Agency chief 
Satsuki Eda and began urging other ruling parties' members to 
join. 
  But the JNP suspended its campaign as ruling parties fell 
into deeper disagreement over selection of Hosokawa's successor. 
  Another reason for the suspension was that some JNP members 
objected to allying with Shinseito and Komeito -- two powerful 
forces in the coalition. 

</TEXT>

