<H3> <TI>   Forming Government `More Important' Than Budget </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Forming Government `More Important' Than Budget </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1504152894 Tokyo KYODO in English 1503 GMT 15 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1504152894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 15 KYODO -- Ichiro Ozawa, the ruling 
coalition's chief strategist, said Friday [15 April] that it is 
much more important to form a stable government than to enact 
the overdue state budget for fiscal 1994 that started April 1. 
  At a news conference, Ozawa said, "there are opinions urging 
enactment of the budget but it is much more important to 
establish a stable political structure through necessary 
discussions." 
  Ozawa, secretary general of the coalition's core party 
Shinseito [Japan Renewal Party], has urged other coalition 
components to cement agreement on such key issues as tax reform 
and the stance toward North Korea's suspected nuclear program 
before picking a successor to Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa, 
who on April 8 said he will step down. 
  Meanwhile, Hajime Funada, a senior Shinseito member, said 
Friday that agreement on tax reform is the minimum requirement 
for policy discussions that start Saturday among deputy heads of 
coalition parties. 
  Speaking at a ceremony to commemorate the establishment of 
the party's chapter in Ustunomiya, Tochigi Prefecture, Funada 
also said that Shinseito will play a key role in selecting a 
successor to Hosokawa. 

</TEXT>

