<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Corporate Bankruptcies Decrease in 1993 </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Corporate Bankruptcies Decrease in 1993 </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1504053694 Tokyo KYODO in English 0437 GMT 15 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1504053694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 15 KYODO -- The number of corporate 
bankruptcies in Japan fell 2.9 percent in fiscal 1993 for the 
first dip in four years, despite staying above 14,000 for the 
second straight year, a private credit research agency reported 
Friday [15 April]. 
  Corporate failures with liabilities of 10 million yen or 
more 
numbered 14,019 in the year ended March 31, while liabilities 
left by the bankrupt firms slid 10.7 percent to 6.65 trillion 
yen for the second consecutive yearly fall, Teikoku Databank 
said. 
  The amount of liabilities was the third largest on record, 
it 
said. The record for liabilities was 7.77 trillion yen in 
fiscal 1991 when the economy was hard hit by a stronger yen. 
  Despite the overall decline in business failures, the number 
of recession-induced bankruptcies or those going bankrupt due to 
poor sales climbed 14.6 percent to 8,645, signaling that the 
economic slump still drags on, the agency said. 
  This type of bankruptcy accounted for 61.7 percent of total 
failures, up 9.5 percentage points from the previous year, it 
said. 
  Corporate failures were at high levels throughout the entire 
year with over 1,000 failures reported each month, during the 
worst economic slump in decades. 
  The findings come at a time when the economy is showing 
brighter signs in some sectors and as Bank of Japan Governor 
Yasushi Mieno has declared the worst is over. 
  But Teikoku Databank said Japan is still mired in the 
prolonged economic slowdown despite signs of recovery in some 
sectors, and noted that a full-fledged recovery is not expected 
until 1995, judging from such negative factors as the strong yen 
and an increase in long-term interest rates. 
  In March, corporate failures fell 4.3 percent from a year 
earlier to 1,282 cases with liabilities shrinking 40.2 percent 
to 463.62 billion yen, the agency said. 
  March was the second consecutive month in which business 
failures fell from the year-earlier level, but it was the first 
time in three months they have risen above 1,200, it said. 
  In the latest reporting month, the number of 
recession-induced failures dropped 5.8 percent from a year 
earlier, but their share of total bankruptcies exceeded 60 
percent for the eighth month in a row. 
  Such bankruptcies totaled 789 cases, compared with 838 cases 
a year earlier. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>
